===Etymology 1===
{{etymid|ja|kome}}
<div style="float:right;">
{{wp|ja:}}
{{wp|Rice}}
</div>
{{ja-kanjitab|こめ|yomi=k}}
{{IPAfont|⟨ko<sub>2</sub>me<sub>2</sub>⟩}} → *{{IPAfont|/kəməj/}} → {{IPAfont|/kome/}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|-}}. First appears in the ''{{w|Nihon Shoki}}'' of 720 {{CE}}, with the phonetic ''{{w|man'yōgana}}'' spelling {{ja-r|linkto=-|rom=-|渠%梅|こ%め}}.<ref name="KDJ2">{{R:Nihon Kokugo Daijiten 2|米}}</ref> In turn, from {{inh|ja|jpx-pro|*kəmay}}.

Many theories exist regarding the ultimate derivation:
* Perhaps from {{ja-r|籠め|こめ}}, the {{ja-ryk|籠める|こめる|to [[do]] with one's [[heart]]}}, from the way rice is farmed. The accent of ''kome'' in the Heian period is <LL>, while ''kome-'' in the Heian period is <L->. {{rfv-etym|ja}}
* Possibly cognate with {{ncog|mkh-vie-pro|*kəːm||[[cooked rice]]}}, modern {{m|vi|cơm}}. {{rfv-etym|ja}}
* Possibly cognate with {{ncog|map-pro|*Semay}} and {{ncog|och|-}} {{och-l|糜}}.<ref>{{cite-journal|en|author=Laurent Sagart|title=How Many Independent Rice Vocabularies in Asia?|work=Rice|page=121–133|date=2011-12|url=https://thericejournal.springeropen.com/articles/10.1007/s12284-011-9077-8|volume=4|issue=3-4|issn=1939-8425|doi=10.1007/s12284-011-9077-8}}</ref><ref>{{cite-journal|en|author=Martine Robbeets|title=Austronesian influence and Transeurasian ancestry in Japanese: A case of farming/language dispersal|work=Language Dynamics and Change|page=210–251|date=2017-01-01|url=https://brill.com/view/journals/ldc/7/2/article-p210_4.xml|volume=7|issue=2|issn=2210-5824|doi=10.1163/22105832-00702005}}</ref> However, this is extremely speculative; none of the known derivations from {{ncog|map-pro|*Semay}} develop initial /k/, nor is this shift explainable by any known mechanism within Japonic.

